segments.text: Hours spent cleaning and scrubbing.
She poured buckets of water and soap and swept them up with the big squeegee.
She put all the chairs on the tables, not before cleaning them too.
She polished the bar and dusted the bottles, washed all the glasses, and placed them to dry on towels.
While waiting for the floor to dry, she stood on a chair and polished the large glass doors facing the garden.
Using a pile of old newspaper, she found discarded near the armchair.
She even cleaned the marks left by the pictures that had been removed from the walls.
But she left the nails in place, perhaps to remember that once there had been pictures there.
Only the desolate corner where the piano had stood and the marks left by its wheels tore a huge hole of longing in her heart.
After recovering a bit, she headed to the grocery store.
Albert greeted her as if she had come from the moon.
Hello to the prettiest general in the army, said the kind.
Warm man.
And in an instant, he managed to bring a smile to her lips.
She bought laundry detergent and a few basic groceries to have something to eat.
She didn't have a penny in her pocket, and Albert willingly noted her debt.
When she returned to the pink house, she soaked the sheets she had removed from the beds in the large sink behind the kitchen.
After finishing with them, she would move on to the towels.
They may not be very dirty, but they had been lying around for months and must have gathered dust.
She cleaned from top to bottom the two rooms that had been theirs, leaving them sparkling.
Dripping with sweat, she absentmindedly opened the fridge behind the bar and was amazed to find arranged bottles of drinks, even beer bottles.
In the freezer beside it, she found plastic trays full of ice cubes.
She took the large beer glass she had washed, filled it with water and ice cubes, and sipped slowly.
She always loved water.
No matter how much the house was filled with fizzy soft drinks, they never appealed to her.
between the lemonade and orange soda, she loved the water.
It ran down her throat with an inexplicable feeling of happiness spreading within her.
She sat on one of the bar stools, looking around and thinking to herself that everything here had come to a standstill.
Then she glanced outside through the clean glass doors and saw the sprinklers watering Lucy's thirsty garden, and the big China berry tree seemed to look back at her as if to say, thank you.
For a while, she sat quietly with her thoughts, savoring the renewed connection with the house.
Suddenly she heard a car stop at the entrance and tensed up.
A minute later, a tall young man stood at the entrance.
Hello, do you have maybe two rooms available for the weekend?
He asked.
We're four friends on a trip, looking for a place to lay our heads.
And if there's something to eat, that would be great.
She almost told him no, that the place was closed, but something stirred within her.
And as if by itself, she replied, yes, no problem at all.
We're doing a bit of renovation here now, but everything is clean and tidy.
Today you might want to eat dinner out, but tomorrow you can have breakfast here and, if you'd like, dinner too.
Just let me know in advance.
He looked at her with a happy expression.
I'll call them right away.
We'll just drop off our stuff and come back in the evening to sleep," he said and left.
Suddenly, fear filled her.
Have you gone mad?
This isn't your place at all.
What are you thinking?
And now what will you do?
You already told him yes.
What could happen after all?
At most, she'll collect some money, leave some for Yehuda in the drawer, and keep a little for herself for her trouble, so she'll have a few coins.
This she told herself in her heart, until the door opened again and all four stood at the entrance.
Strong, cheerful, with smiles on their faces, they greeted her with a hey almost in harmony.
She noticed they looked at her in wonder.
For a moment, she forgot she was in her cleaning clothes.
The shorts and tank top she had found forgotten and folded on the kitchen shelf, always barefoot.
Come, I'll show you the rooms, she said in embarrassment.
Feeling a bit uncomfortable with her somewhat revealing and neglected appearance, they walked behind her to the rooms area.
She opened the two rooms and the bathroom she had cleaned for herself, hoping to settle in one of them.
A pleasant smell of cleanliness greeted them.
Until you come back, I'll bring you clean towels, too."
She said and left them to arrange their belongings in the rooms.
The four stood, looking at each other.
The first guy who had asked earlier if there was a place abruptly said, What luck!
How clean and pleasant it is here.
Yes, another replied.
But what's with that girl?
Is she running the place all by herself?
Doesn't seem like any cleaner to me.
You'll agree it's a bit odd.
What do you care?
We're just sleeping here between our trips in the area anyway."
On their way out, they told her they'd be happy to have breakfast and dinner tomorrow.
A little while later, she heard their car driving off.
There wasn't much time left for thoughts.
She had to run again to Albert at the grocery store before he closed, returned with a stack of groceries and placed everything in its place.
She now laughed to herself.
When she scrubbed the stove earlier, she wondered why she was cleaning it.
Who would even cook there?
And now, good thing she cleaned it.
How nice to bring this place back to life.
She poured herself a cup of coffee with milk into the beloved beer glass and sat to rest in the armchair.
Suddenly, her eyes rested on the small room door by the bathroom.
Yehuda said some of the paintings were still there.
She stood up at once, opened the door and saw the paintings neatly packed, leaning against the wall.
Slowly she untied the string wrapped around them and opened the wrapping of the first painting.
Her eyes fell on the blue picture in an instant.
Tears welled in her eyes.
It was the most special painting in her eyes.
The one grandmother Lucy always said Joseph must have been drunk when he painted it.
She peeled off its wrapping paper, carefully took it in her hands, and hung it on the same nail where it had been before.
Then she moved on to the watercolor painting of the dune and sycamore trees.
After that came a large, soft charcoal drawing, depicting Lucy sitting in the armchair, the same armchair in the corner.
Embracing her as a baby, maybe two weeks old.
Without realizing it, the house's walls were filled again with Joseph's paintings.
she had already hung almost all of them in exactly their previous places, on the nails still embedded in the walls.

She carefully folded the wrappings, rolled up the string, and intended to put them back in the small room, when suddenly she saw another picture in the corner of the wall to the left, a slightly smaller picture, and immediately knew what it was.
With trembling hands, she began to peel the wrapping paper from it, almost scared of what she would reveal.
First, she saw the front gray hair with the white streak in the front, and then suddenly her beautiful mother's face appeared, gazing deep into her own eyes.
She collapsed into the armchair, holding the picture in both hands and whispered, tears in her eyes.
Hi, mama, see how I'm sorting out a bit of the chaos in life.
